# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: secondary-index
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] In computer science, a **B-tree** is a self-balancing tree data structure that maintains sorted data and allows searches, sequential access, insertions, and deletions in logarithmic time.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] The B-tree generalizes the binary search tree, allowing nodes to have more than two children.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] By allowing more children under one node than a regular self-balancing binary search tree, the B-tree reduces the height of the tree and puts the data in fewer separate blocks.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] This is especially important for trees stored in secondary storage (e.g., disk drives), as these systems have relatively high latency and work with relatively large blocks of data, hence the B-tree's use in databases and file systems.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] This remains a major advantage when the tree is stored in memory, as modern computer systems rely heavily on CPU caches.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Compared to reading from the cache, reading from memory after a cache miss costs significant time.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] While working at Boeing Research Labs, Rudolf Bayer and Edward M.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] McCreight invented B-trees to efficiently manage index pages for large random-access files.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Their basic assumption was that indices would be so voluminous that only small chunks of the tree could fit in the main memory.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Bayer and McCreight's paper *Organization and maintenance of large ordered indices* was first circulated in July 1970 and later published in *Acta Informatica*.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Bayer and McCreight never explained what, if anything, the *B* stands for; *Boeing*, *balanced*, *between*, *broad*, *bushy*, and *Bayer* have been suggested.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Every node, except for the root and the leaves, has at least ⌈*m*/2⌉ children.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] The root node has at least two children unless it is a leaf.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] A non-leaf node with *k* children contains *k*−1 keys.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] The keys of each non-leaf node act as separation values that divide its subtrees.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] For example, if an internal node has 3 child nodes (or subtrees), then it must have 2 keys: *a*1 and *a*2.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] All values in the leftmost subtree will be less than *a*1, all values in the middle subtree will be between *a*1 and *a*2, and all values in the rightmost subtree will be greater than *a*2.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] ) are all nodes except for leaf nodes and the root node.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] They are usually represented as an ordered set of elements and child pointers.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] −1; therefore, each internal node is at least half full.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] implies that two half-full nodes can be joined to make a legal node, and one full node can be split into two legal nodes (if there's room to push one element up into the parent).
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] These properties make it possible to delete and insert new values into a B-tree while also adjusting the tree to preserve its properties.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] The root node's number of children has the same upper limit as internal nodes but has no lower limit.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] −1 elements in the entire tree, the root will be the only node in the tree with no children at all.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] In Knuth's terminology, the "leaf" nodes are the actual data objects/chunks.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] /2-1 if they are not the root) and pointers (one for each key) to nodes carrying the data objects/chunks.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] A B-tree of depth *n*+1 can hold about *U* times as many items as a B-tree of depth *n*, but the cost of search, insert, and delete operations grows with the depth of the tree.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] As with any balanced tree, the cost grows much more slowly than the number of elements.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Some balanced trees store values only at leaf nodes and use different kinds of nodes for leaf nodes and internal nodes.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] B-trees keep values in every node in the tree except leaf nodes.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] The literature on B-trees is not uniform in its terminology.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Bayer and McCreight (1972), Comer (1979), and others define the **order** of a B-tree as the minimum number of keys in a non-root node.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Folk and Zoellick point out that terminology is ambiguous because the maximum number of keys is unclear.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] An order 3 B-tree might hold a maximum of 6 keys or a maximum of 7 keys.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Knuth (1998) avoids the problem by defining the **order** to be the maximum number of children (which is one more than the maximum number of keys).
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Bayer and McCreight (1972) considered the leaf level to be the lowest level of keys, but Knuth considered the leaf level to be one level below the lowest keys.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] There are many possible implementation choices.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] In some designs, the leaves may hold the entire data record; in other designs, the leaves may only hold pointers to the data record.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Those choices are not fundamental to the idea of a B-tree.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] For simplicity, most authors assume there is a fixed number of keys that fit in a node.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] The basic assumption is that the key size and node size are both fixed.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] In practice, variable-length keys may be employed.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] As with other trees, B-trees can be represented as a collection of three types of nodes: *root*, *internal* (a.k.a. interior), and *leaf*.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] To maintain the predefined range of child nodes, internal nodes may be joined or split.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Usually, the number of keys is chosen to vary between d and $2d$ , where d is the minimum number of keys, and $d+1$ is the minimum degree or branching factor of the tree.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] The factor of 2 will guarantee that nodes can be split or combined.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] If an internal node has $2d$ keys, then adding a key to that node can be accomplished by splitting the hypothetical $2d+1$ key node into two d key nodes and moving the key that would have been in the middle to the parent node.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Each split node has the required minimum number of keys.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Similarly, if an internal node and its neighbor each have d keys, then a key may be deleted from the internal node by combining it with its neighbor.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Deleting the key would make the internal node have $d-1$ keys; joining the neighbor would add d keys plus one more key brought down from the neighbor's parent.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] The result is an entirely full node of $2d$ keys.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] A B-tree is kept balanced after insertion by splitting a would-be overfilled node, of $2d+1$ keys, into two d-key siblings and inserting the mid-value key into the parent.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Depth only increases when the root is split, maintaining balance.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Similarly, a B-tree is kept balanced after deletion by merging or redistributing keys among siblings to maintain the d-key minimum for non-root nodes.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] A merger reduces the number of keys in the parent, potentially forcing it to merge or redistribute keys with its siblings, and so on.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] The only change in depth occurs when the root has two children, of d and (transitionally) $d-1$ keys, in which case the two siblings and parent are merged, reducing the depth by one.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] This depth will increase slowly as elements are added to the tree, but an increase in the overall depth is infrequent, and results in all leaf nodes being one more node farther away from the root.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Because a range of child nodes is permitted, B-trees do not need re-balancing as frequently as other self-balancing search trees, but may waste some space since nodes are not entirely full.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] B-trees have substantial advantages over alternative implementations when the time to access the data of a node greatly exceeds the time spent processing that data, because the cost of accessing the node may then be amortized over multiple operations within the node.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] This usually occurs when the node data are stored in secondary storage, such as disk drives.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] By maximizing the number of keys within each internal node, the height of the tree decreases, and the number of expensive node accesses is reduced.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] In addition, rebalancing of the tree occurs less frequently.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] The maximum number of child nodes depends on the information that must be stored for each child node and the size of a full disk block or an analogous size in secondary storage.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] While 2–3 B-trees are easier to explain, practical B-trees using secondary storage need a large number of child nodes to improve performance.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] The term **B-tree** may refer to a specific design or a general class of designs.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] In the narrow sense, a B-tree stores keys in its internal nodes but need not store those keys in the records at the leaves.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] The general class includes variations such as the B+ tree, the B* tree and the B*+ tree.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Sorting and searching algorithms can be characterized by the number of comparison operations that must be performed using order notation.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] A binary search of a sorted table with N records, for example, can be done in roughly ⌈ log2 *N* ⌉ comparisons.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] If the table had 1,000,000 records, then a specific record could be located with at most 20 comparisons: ⌈ log2 (1,000,000) ⌉ = 20.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Large databases have historically been kept on disk drives.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] The time required to read a record on a disk drive far exceeds the time needed to compare keys once the record is available due to seek time and rotational delay.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] The seek time may be 0 to 20 or more milliseconds, and the rotational delay averages about half the rotation period.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] For a 7200 RPM drive, the rotation period is 8.33 milliseconds.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] For a drive such as the Seagate ST3500320NS, the track-to-track seek time is 0.8 milliseconds and the average reading seek time is 8.5 milliseconds.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] For simplicity, assume reading from disk takes about 10 milliseconds.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] The time required to locate one record out of a million in the example above would be 20 disk reads, each taking 10 milliseconds, which equals 0.2 seconds.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] The search time is reduced because individual records are grouped together in a disk **block**.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] A disk block might be 16 kilobytes in size.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] If each record is 160 bytes, then 100 records could be stored in each block.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] The disk read time above was actually for an entire block.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Once the disk head is in position, one or more disk blocks can be read with little delay.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] With 100 records per block, the last 6 or so comparisons don't need to do any disk reads—the comparisons are all within the last disk block read.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] To speed up the search further, the time to do the first 13 to 14 comparisons (which each required disk access) must be reduced.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] A B-tree index can be used to improve performance.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] A B-tree index creates a multi-level tree structure that breaks a database down into fixed-size blocks or pages.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Each level of this tree can be used to link those pages via an address location, allowing one page (known as a node, or internal page) to refer to another with leaf pages at the lowest level.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] One page is typically the starting point of the tree, or the "root".
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] This is where the search for a particular key would begin, traversing a path that terminates in a leaf.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Most pages in this structure will be leaf pages which refer to specific table rows.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Because each node (or internal page) can have more than two children, a B-tree index will usually have a shorter height (the distance from the root to the farthest leaf) than a Binary Search Tree.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] In the example above, initial disk reads narrowed the search range by a factor of two.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] That can be improved by creating an auxiliary index that contains the first record in each disk block (sometimes called a sparse index).
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] This auxiliary index would be 1% of the size of the original database, but it can be searched quickly.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Finding an entry in the auxiliary index would tell us which block to search in the main database; after searching the auxiliary index, we would have to search only that one block of the main database—at a cost of one more disk read.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] In the above example, the index would hold 10,000 entries and would take at most 14 comparisons to return a result.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Like the main database, the last six or so comparisons in the auxiliary index would be on the same disk block.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] The index could be searched in about eight disk reads, and the desired record could be accessed in 9 disk reads.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Creating an auxiliary index can be repeated to make an auxiliary index to the auxiliary index.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] That would create an aux-aux index that would need only 100 entries and would fit in one disk block.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Instead of reading 14 disk blocks to find the desired record, we only need to read 3 blocks.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] This blocking is the core idea behind the creation of the B-tree, where disk blocks form a hierarchy of levels to make up the index.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Reading and searching the first (and only) block of the aux-aux index, which is the root of the tree, identifies the relevant block in aux-index in the level below.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Reading and searching that aux-index block identifies the relevant block to read until the final level, known as the leaf level, identifies a record in the main database.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Instead of 150 milliseconds, we need only 30 milliseconds to get the record.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] The auxiliary indices have turned the search problem from a binary search requiring roughly log2 *N* disk reads to one requiring only log*b* *N* disk reads where b is the blocking factor (the number of entries per block: *b* = 100 entries per block in our example; log100 1,000,000 = 3 reads).
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] In practice, if the main database is being frequently searched, the aux-aux index and much of the aux index may reside in a disk cache, so they would not incur a disk read.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] The B-tree remains the standard index implementation in almost all relational databases, and many nonrelational databases use it as well.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] If the database does not change, then compiling the index is simple to do, and the index need never be changed.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] If there are changes, managing the database and its index requires additional computation.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Deleting records from a database is relatively easy.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] The index can stay the same, and the record can just be marked as deleted.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] If there are a large number of lazy deletions, then searching and storage become less efficient.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Insertions can be very slow in a sorted sequential file because room for the inserted record must be made.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Inserting a record before the first record requires shifting all of the records down one.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Such an operation is just too expensive to be practical.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Instead of densely packing all the records in a block, the block can have some free space to allow for subsequent insertions.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Those spaces would be marked as if they were "deleted" records.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Both insertions and deletions are fast as long as space is available on a block.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] If an insertion won't fit on the block, then some free space on some nearby block must be found and the auxiliary indices adjusted.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] The best case is that enough space is available nearby so that the amount of block reorganization can be minimized.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Alternatively, some out-of-sequence disk blocks may be used.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] The B-tree uses all of the ideas described above.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] In addition, a B-tree minimizes waste by making sure the interior nodes are at least half full.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] A B-tree can handle an arbitrary number of insertions and deletions.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Let *h* ≥ –1 be the height of the classic B-tree (see Tree (data structure) § Terminology for the tree height definition).
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Let *n* ≥ 0 be the number of entries in the tree.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Let *m* be the maximum number of children a node can have.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] It can be shown (by induction for example) that a B-tree of height *h* with all its nodes completely filled has *n* = *m**h*+1–1 entries.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Let d be the minimum number of children an internal (non-root) node must have.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Searching is similar to searching a binary search tree.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Starting at the root, the tree is recursively traversed from top to bottom.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] At each level, the search reduces its field of view to the child pointer (subtree) whose range includes the search value.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] A subtree's range is defined by the values, or keys, contained in its parent node.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] These limiting values are also known as separation values.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Binary search is typically (but not necessarily) used within nodes to find the separation values and child tree of interest.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] To insert a new element, search the tree to find the leaf node where the new element should be added.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Values less than the median are put in the new left node, and values greater than the median are put in the new right node, with the median acting as a separation value.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] The separation value is inserted in the node's parent, which may cause it to be split, and so on.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] If the node has no parent (i.e., the node was the root), create a new root above this node (increasing the height of the tree).
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] If the splitting goes all the way up to the root, it creates a new root with a single separator value and two children, which is why the lower bound on the size of internal nodes does not apply to the root.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] The maximum number of elements per node is *U*−1.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] When a node is split, one element moves to the parent, but one element is added.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] So, it must be possible to divide the maximum number *U*−1 of elements into two legal nodes.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] If this number is odd, then *U*=2*L* and one of the new nodes contains (*U*−2)/2 = *L*−1 elements, and hence is a legal node, and the other contains one more element, and hence it is legal too.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] If *U*−1 is even, then *U*=2*L*−1, so there are 2*L*−2 elements in the node.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Half of this number is *L*−1, which is the minimum number of elements allowed per node.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] An alternative algorithm supports a single pass down the tree from the root to the node where the insertion will take place, splitting any full nodes encountered on the way pre-emptively.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] This prevents the need to recall the parent nodes into memory, which may be expensive if the nodes are on secondary storage.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] However, to use this algorithm, we must be able to send one element to the parent and split the remaining *U*−2 elements into two legal nodes, without adding a new element.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] This requires *U* = 2*L* rather than *U* = 2*L*−1, which accounts for why some textbooks impose this requirement in defining B-trees.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] There are two popular strategies for deletion from a B-tree.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Do a single pass down the tree, but before entering (visiting) a node, restructure the tree so that once the key to be deleted is encountered, it can be deleted without triggering the need for any further restructuring.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] The algorithm below uses the former strategy.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Deleting an element may put its node under the minimum number of elements and children.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] The procedures for these cases are listed below.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] If the value is in a leaf node, simply delete it from the node.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] If underflow happens, rebalance the tree as described in the section "Rebalancing after deletion" below.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Each element in an internal node acts as a separation value for two subtrees; we need to find a replacement for separation.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Note that the largest element in the left subtree is still less than the separator.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Likewise, the smallest element in the right subtree is still greater than the separator.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Both of those elements are in leaf nodes, and either one can be the new separator for the two subtrees.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] The previous step deleted an element (the new separator) from a leaf node.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] If that leaf node is now deficient (has fewer than the required number of nodes), then rebalance the tree starting from the leaf node.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Rebalancing starts from a leaf and proceeds toward the root until the tree is balanced.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] If deleting an element from a node has brought it under the minimum size, then some elements must be redistributed to bring all nodes up to the minimum.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Usually, the redistribution involves moving an element from a sibling node that has more than the minimum number of nodes.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] That redistribution operation is called a **rotation**.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] If no sibling can spare an element, then the deficient node must be **merged** with a sibling.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] The merge causes the parent to lose a separator element, so the parent may become deficient and need rebalancing.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] The merging and rebalancing may continue all the way to the root.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Since the minimum element count doesn't apply to the root, making the root be the only deficient node is not a problem.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] While freshly loaded databases tend to have good sequential behaviour, this behaviour becomes increasingly difficult to maintain as a database grows, resulting in more random I/O and performance challenges.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] A common special case is adding a large amount of *pre-sorted* data into an initially empty B-tree.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] While it is quite possible to simply perform a series of successive inserts, inserting sorted data results in a tree composed almost entirely of half-full nodes.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Instead, a special "bulk loading" algorithm can be used to produce a more efficient tree with a higher branching factor.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] When the input is sorted, all insertions are at the rightmost edge of the tree, and in particular any time a node is split, we are guaranteed that no more insertions will take place in the left half.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] When bulk loading, we take advantage of this, and instead of splitting overfull nodes evenly, split them as *unevenly* as possible: leave the left node completely full and create a right node with zero keys and one child (in violation of the usual B-tree rules).
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] At the end of bulk loading, the tree is composed almost entirely of completely full nodes; only the rightmost node on each level may be less than full.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Because those nodes may also be less than *half* full, to re-establish the normal B-tree rules, combine such nodes with their (guaranteed full) left siblings and divide the keys to produce two nodes at least half full.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] The only node which lacks a full left sibling is the root, which is permitted to be less than half full.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] In addition to its use in databases, the B-tree (or § Variants) is also used in filesystems to allow quick random access to an arbitrary block in a particular file.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] The basic problem is turning the file block i address into a disk block address.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Some early operating systems, and some highly specialized ones, required the application to allocate the maximum size of a file when the file was created.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] The file can then be allocated as contiguous disk blocks.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] In that case, to convert the file block address i into a disk block address, the operating system simply adds the file block address i to the address of the first disk block constituting the file.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] The scheme is simple, but the file cannot exceed its created size.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] All modern, mainstream operating systems allow a file to grow.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] The resulting disk blocks may not be contiguous, so mapping logical blocks to physical blocks is more involved.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] MS-DOS, for example, used a simple File Allocation Table (FAT).
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] The FAT has an entry for each disk block, and that entry identifies whether its block is used by a file and if so, which block (if any) is the next disk block of the same file.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] So, the allocation of each file is represented as a linked list in the table.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] In order to find the disk address of file block i , the operating system (or disk utility) must sequentially follow the file's linked list in the FAT.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Worse, to find a free disk block, it must sequentially scan the FAT.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] For MS-DOS, that was not a huge penalty because the disks and files were small and the FAT had few entries and relatively short file chains.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] In the FAT12 filesystem (used on floppy disks and early hard disks), there were no more than 4,080 entries, and the FAT would usually be resident in memory.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] As disks got bigger, the FAT architecture began to confront penalties.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] On a large disk using FAT, it may be necessary to perform disk reads to learn the disk location of a file block to be read or written.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] TOPS-20 used a 0 to 2 level tree that has similarities to a B-tree.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] If the file fit in a 512 (29) word block, then the file directory would point to that physical disk block.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] If the file fit in 218 words, then the directory would point to an aux index; the 512 words of that index would either be NULL (the block isn't allocated) or point to the physical address of the block.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] If the file fit in 227 words, then the directory would point to a block holding an aux-aux index; each entry would either be NULL or point to an aux index.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Consequently, the physical disk block for a 227 word file could be located in two disk reads and read on the third.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Apple's filesystem HFS+ and APFS, Microsoft's NTFS, AIX (jfs2) and some Linux filesystems, such as Bcachefs, Btrfs and ext4, use B-trees.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] B*-trees are used in the HFS and Reiser4 file systems.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] DragonFly BSD's HAMMER file system uses a modified B+-tree.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] A B-tree grows slower with growing data amount, than the linearity of a linked list.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Compared to a skip list, both structures have the same performance, but the B-tree scales better for growing *n*.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] A T-tree, for main memory database systems, is similar but more compact.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Lehman and Yao showed that all the read locks could be avoided (and thus concurrent access greatly improved) by linking the tree blocks at each level together with a "next" pointer.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] This results in a tree structure where both insertion and search operations descend from the root to the leaf.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Write locks are only required as a tree block is modified.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] This maximizes access concurrency by multiple users, an important consideration for databases and/or other B-tree-based ISAM storage methods.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] The cost associated with this improvement is that empty pages cannot be removed from the btree during normal operations.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] United States Patent 5283894, granted in 1994, appears to show a way to use a 'Meta Access Method' to allow concurrent B+ tree access and modification without locks.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] The technique accesses the tree 'upwards' for both searches and updates by means of additional in-memory indexes that point at the blocks in each level in the block cache.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] No reorganization for deletes is needed and there are no 'next' pointers in each block as in Lehman and Yao.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] Since B-trees are similar in structure to red-black trees, parallel algorithms for red-black trees can be applied to B-trees as well.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] A Maple tree is a B-tree developed for use in the Linux kernel to reduce lock contention in virtual memory management.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] (a,b)-trees are generalizations of B-trees.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] B-trees require that each internal node have a minimum of $\lfloor K/2\rfloor +1$ children and a maximum of K children, for some preset value of K .
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] In contrast, an (a,b)-tree allows the minimum number of children for an internal node to be set arbitrarily low.
[src:secondary-index/b-tree] In an (a,b)-tree, each internal node has between a and b children, for some preset values of a and b.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] A **bitmap index** is a special kind of database index that uses bitmaps.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] Bitmap indexes have traditionally been considered to work well for *low-cardinality columns*, which have a modest number of distinct values, either absolutely, or relative to the number of records that contain the data.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] The extreme case of low cardinality is Boolean data (e.g., does a resident in a city have internet access?), which has two values, True and False.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] Bitmap indexes use bit arrays (commonly called bitmaps) and answer queries by performing bitwise logical operations on these bitmaps.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] Bitmap indexes have a significant space and performance advantage over other structures for query of such data.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] Some researchers argue that bitmap indexes are also useful for moderate or even high-cardinality data (e.g., unique-valued data) which is accessed in a read-only manner, and queries access multiple bitmap-indexed columns using the AND, OR or XOR operators extensively.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] Bitmap indexes are also useful in data warehousing applications for joining a large fact table to smaller dimension tables such as those arranged in a star schema.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] On the left, Identifier refers to the unique number assigned to each resident, HasInternet is the data to be indexed, the content of the bitmap index is shown as two columns under the heading *bitmaps*.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] Each column in the left illustration under the Bitmaps header is a *bitmap* in the bitmap index.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] In this case, there are two such bitmaps, one for "has internet" *Yes* and one for "has internet" *No*.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] It is easy to see that each bit in bitmap *Y* shows whether a particular row refers to a person who has internet access.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] This is the simplest form of bitmap index.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] Most columns will have more distinct values.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] For example, the sales amount is likely to have a much larger number of distinct values.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] Variations on the bitmap index can effectively index this data as well.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] We briefly review three such variations.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] Note: Many of the references cited here are reviewed at (John Wu (2007)).
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] For those who might be interested in experimenting with some of the ideas mentioned here, many of them are implemented in open source software such as FastBit, the Lemur Bitmap Index C++ Library, the Roaring Bitmap Java library and the Apache Hive Data Warehouse system.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] For historical reasons, bitmap compression and inverted list compression were developed as separate lines of research, and only later were recognized as solving essentially the same problem.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] Software can compress each bitmap in a bitmap index to save space.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] There has been considerable amount of work on this subject.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] These compression methods require very little effort to compress and decompress.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] More importantly, bitmaps compressed with BBC, WAH, COMPAX, PLWAH, EWAH and CONCISE can directly participate in bitwise operations without decompression.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] This gives them considerable advantages over generic compression techniques such as LZ77.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] BBC compression and its derivatives are used in a commercial database management system.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] BBC is effective in both reducing index sizes and maintaining query performance.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] BBC encodes the bitmaps in bytes, while WAH encodes in words, better matching current CPUs.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] Similar considerations can be done for CONCISE and Enhanced Word-Aligned Hybrid.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] The performance of schemes such as BBC, WAH, PLWAH, EWAH, COMPAX and CONCISE is dependent on the order of the rows.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] A simple lexicographical sort can divide the index size by 9 and make indexes several times faster.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] The larger the table, the more important it is to sort the rows.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] Reshuffling techniques have also been proposed to achieve the same results of sorting when indexing streaming data.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] Basic bitmap indexes use one bitmap for each distinct value.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] It is possible to reduce the number of bitmaps used by using a different encoding method.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] For example, it is possible to encode C distinct values using log(C) bitmaps with binary encoding.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] This reduces the number of bitmaps, further saving space, but to answer any query, most of the bitmaps have to be accessed.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] This makes it potentially not as effective as scanning a vertical projection of the base data, also known as a materialized view or projection index.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] Finding the optimal encoding method that balances (arbitrary) query performance, index size and index maintenance remains a challenge.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] For high-cardinality columns, it is useful to bin the values, where each bin covers multiple values and build the bitmaps to represent the values in each bin.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] This approach reduces the number of bitmaps used regardless of encoding method.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] However, binned indexes can only answer some queries without examining the base data.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] For example, if a bin covers the range from 0.1 to 0.2, then when the user asks for all values less than 0.15, all rows that fall in the bin are possible hits and have to be checked to verify whether they are actually less than 0.15.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] The process of checking the base data is known as the candidate check.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] In most cases, the time used by the candidate check is significantly longer than the time needed to work with the bitmap index.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] Therefore, binned indexes exhibit irregular performance.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] They can be very fast for some queries, but much slower if the query does not exactly match a bin.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] The concept of bitmap index was first introduced by Professor Israel Spiegler and Rafi Maayan in their research "Storage and Retrieval Considerations of Binary Data Bases", published in 1985.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] The first commercial database product to implement a bitmap index was Computer Corporation of America's Model 204.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] Patrick O'Neil published a paper about this implementation in 1987.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] This implementation is a hybrid between the basic bitmap index (without compression) and the list of Row Identifiers (RID-list).
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] Overall, the index is organized as a B+tree.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] When the column cardinality is low, each leaf node of the B-tree would contain long list of RIDs.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] In this case, it requires less space to represent the RID-lists as bitmaps.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] Since each bitmap represents one distinct value, this is the basic bitmap index.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] As the column cardinality increases, each bitmap becomes sparse and it may take more disk space to store the bitmaps than to store the same content as RID-lists.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] In this case, it switches to use the RID-lists, which makes it a B+tree index.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] One of the strongest reasons for using bitmap indexes is that the intermediate results produced from them are also bitmaps and can be efficiently reused in further operations to answer more complex queries.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] Many programming languages support this as a bit array data structure.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] For example, Java has the `BitSet` class and .NET have the BitArray class.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] Some database systems that do not offer persistent bitmap indexes use bitmaps internally to speed up query processing.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] For example, PostgreSQL versions 8.1 and later implement a "bitmap index scan" optimization to speed up arbitrarily complex logical operations between available indexes on a single table.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] A bitmap index scan combines expressions on different indexes, thus requiring only one index per column to support all possible queries on a table.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] Applying this access strategy to B-tree indexes can also combine range queries on multiple columns.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] In this approach, a temporary in-memory bitmap is created with one bit for each row in the table (1 MB can thus store over 8 million entries).
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] Next, the results from each index are combined into the bitmap using bitwise operations.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] After all conditions are evaluated, the bitmap contains a "1" for rows that matched the expression.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] Finally, the bitmap is traversed and matching rows are retrieved.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] In addition to efficiently combining indexes, this also improves locality of reference of table accesses, because all rows are fetched sequentially from the main table.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] The internal bitmap is discarded after the query.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] If there are too many rows in the table to use 1 bit per row, a "lossy" bitmap is created instead, with a single bit per disk page.
[src:secondary-index/bitmap-index] In this case, the bitmap is just used to determine which pages to fetch; the filter criteria are then applied to all rows in matching pages.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] A **database index** is a data structure that improves the speed of data retrieval operations on a database table at the cost of additional writes and storage space to maintain the index data structure.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] Indexes are used to quickly locate data without having to search every row in a database table every time said table is accessed.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] Indexes can be created using one or more columns of a database table, providing the basis for both rapid random lookups and efficient access of ordered records.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] An index is a copy of selected columns of data, from a table, that is designed to enable very efficient search.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] An index normally includes a "key" or direct link to the original row of data from which it was copied, to allow the complete row to be retrieved efficiently.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] Some databases extend the power of indexing by letting developers create indexes on column values that have been transformed by functions or expressions.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] For example, an index could be created on `upper(last_name)`, which would only store the upper-case versions of the `last_name` field in the index.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] Another option sometimes supported is the use of partial index, where index entries are created only for those records that satisfy some conditional expression.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] A further aspect of flexibility is to permit indexing on user-defined functions, as well as expressions formed from an assortment of built-in functions.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] Most database software includes indexing technology that enables sub-linear time lookup to improve performance, as linear search is inefficient for large databases.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] Suppose a database contains N data items and one must be retrieved based on the value of one of the fields.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] A simple implementation retrieves and examines each item according to the test.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] If there is only one matching item, this can stop when it finds that single item, but if there are multiple matches, it must test everything.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] This means that the number of operations in the average case is O(N) or linear time.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] Since databases may contain many objects, and since lookup is a common operation, it is often desirable to improve performance.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] An index is any data structure that improves the performance of lookup.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] There are many different data structures used for this purpose.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] There are complex design trade-offs involving lookup performance, index size, and index-update performance.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] Many index designs exhibit logarithmic (O(log(N))) lookup performance and in some applications it is possible to achieve flat (O(1)) performance.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] Indexes are used to police database constraints, such as UNIQUE, EXCLUSION, PRIMARY KEY and FOREIGN KEY.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] An index may be declared as UNIQUE, which creates an implicit constraint on the underlying table.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] Database systems usually implicitly create an index on a set of columns declared PRIMARY KEY, and some are capable of using an already-existing index to police this constraint.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] Many database systems require that both referencing and referenced sets of columns in a FOREIGN KEY constraint are indexed, thus improving performance of inserts, updates and deletes to the tables participating in the constraint.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] Some database systems support an EXCLUSION constraint that ensures that, for a newly inserted or updated record, a certain predicate holds for no other record.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] This can be used to implement a UNIQUE constraint (with equality predicate) or more complex constraints, like ensuring that no overlapping time ranges or no intersecting geometry objects would be stored in the table.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] An index supporting fast searching for records satisfying the predicate is required to police such a constraint.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] The data is present in arbitrary order, but the **logical ordering** is specified by the index.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] The data rows may be spread throughout the table regardless of the value of the indexed column or expression.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] The non-clustered index tree contains the index keys in sorted order, with the leaf level of the index containing the pointer to the record (page and the row number in the data page in page-organized engines; row offset in file-organized engines).
[src:secondary-index/database-index] There can be more than one non-clustered index on a database table.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] Clustering alters the data block into a certain distinct order to match the index, resulting in the row data being stored in order.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] Therefore, only one clustered index can be created on a given database table.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] Clustered indexes can greatly increase overall speed of retrieval, but usually only where the data is accessed sequentially in the same or reverse order of the clustered index, or when a range of items is selected.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] Since the physical records are in this sort order on disk, the next row item in the sequence is immediately before or after the last one, and so fewer data block reads are required.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] The primary feature of a clustered index is therefore the ordering of the physical data rows in accordance with the index blocks that point to them.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] Some databases separate the data and index blocks into separate files, others put two completely different data blocks within the same physical file(s).
[src:secondary-index/database-index] When multiple databases and multiple tables are joined, it is called a **cluster** (not to be confused with clustered index described previously).
[src:secondary-index/database-index] The records for the tables sharing the value of a cluster key shall be stored together in the same or nearby data blocks.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] This may improve the joins of these tables on the cluster key, since the matching records are stored together and less I/O is required to locate them.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] The cluster configuration defines the data layout in the tables that are parts of the cluster.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] A cluster can be keyed with a B-tree index or a hash table.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] The data block where the table record is stored is defined by the value of the cluster key.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] The order that the index definition defines the columns in is important.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] It is possible to retrieve a set of row identifiers using only the first indexed column.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] However, it is not possible or efficient (on most databases) to retrieve the set of row identifiers using only the second or greater indexed column.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] For example, in a phone book organized by city first, then by last name, and then by first name, in a particular city, one can easily extract the list of all phone numbers.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] However, it would be very tedious to find all the phone numbers for a particular last name.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] One would have to look within each city's section for the entries with that last name.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] Some databases can do this, others just won't use the index.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] Then a sequential lookup checks the matching with `first_name`.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] So, to improve the performance, one must ensure that the index is created on the order of search columns.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] Indexes are useful for many applications but come with some limitations.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] Consider the following SQL statement: `SELECT first_name FROM people WHERE last_name = 'Smith';`.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] To process this statement without an index the database software must look at the last_name column on every row in the table (this is known as a full table scan).
[src:secondary-index/database-index] With an index the database simply follows the index data structure (typically a B-tree) until the Smith entry has been found; this is much less computationally expensive than a full table scan.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] Consider this SQL statement: `SELECT email_address FROM customers WHERE email_address LIKE '%@wikipedia.org';`.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] This query would yield an email address for every customer whose email address ends with "@wikipedia.org", but even if the email_address column has been indexed the database must perform a full index scan.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] This is because the index is built with the assumption that words go from left to right.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] With a wildcard at the beginning of the search-term, the database software is unable to use the underlying index data structure (in other words, the WHERE-clause is *not sargable*).
[src:secondary-index/database-index] This problem can be solved through the addition of another index created on `reverse(email_address)` and a SQL query like this: `SELECT email_address FROM customers WHERE reverse(email_address) LIKE reverse('%@wikipedia.org');`.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] This puts the wild-card at the right-most part of the query (now gro.aidepikiw@%), which the index on reverse(email_address) can satisfy.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] When the wildcard characters are used on both sides of the search word as *%wikipedia.org%*, the index available on this field is not used.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] Rather only a sequential search is performed, which takes ⁠ $O(N)$ ⁠ time.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] To mitigate this, a full-text indexing approach can be used.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] A bitmap index is a special kind of indexing that stores the bulk of its data as bit arrays (bitmaps) and answers most queries by performing bitwise logical operations on these bitmaps.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] The most commonly used indexes, such as B+ trees, are most efficient if the values they index do not repeat or repeat a small number of times.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] In contrast, the bitmap index is designed for cases where the values of a variable repeat very frequently.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] For example, the sex field in a customer database usually contains at most three distinct values: male, female or unknown (not recorded).
[src:secondary-index/database-index] For such variables, the bitmap index can have a significant performance advantage over the commonly used trees.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] A dense index in databases is a file with pairs of keys and pointers for every record in the data file.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] Every key in this file is associated with a particular pointer to *a record* in the sorted data file.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] In clustered indices with duplicate keys, the dense index points *to the first record* with that key.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] A sparse index in databases is a file with pairs of keys and pointers for every block in the data file.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] Every key in this file is associated with a particular pointer *to the block* in the sorted data file.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] In clustered indices with duplicate keys, the sparse index points *to the lowest search key* in each block.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] A reverse-key index reverses the key value before entering it in the index.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] Reversing the key value is particularly useful for indexing data such as sequence numbers, where new key values monotonically increase.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] An inverted index maps a content word to the document containing it, thereby allowing full-text searches.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] The primary index contains the key fields of the table and a pointer to the non-key fields of the table.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] The primary index is created automatically when the table is created in the database.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] It is used to index fields that are neither ordering fields nor key fields (there is no assurance that the file is organized on key field or primary key field).
[src:secondary-index/database-index] One index entry for every tuple in the data file (dense index) contains the value of the indexed attribute and pointer to the block or record.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] Another type of index used in database systems is linear hashing.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] Indices can be implemented using a variety of data structures.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] Popular indices include balanced trees, B+ trees and hashes.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] In Microsoft SQL Server, the leaf node of the clustered index corresponds to the actual data, not simply a pointer to data that resides elsewhere, as is the case with a non-clustered index.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] Each relation can have a single clustered index and many unclustered indices.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] An index is typically being accessed concurrently by several transactions and processes, and thus needs concurrency control.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] While in principle indexes can utilize the common database concurrency control methods, specialized concurrency control methods for indexes exist, which are applied in conjunction with the common methods for a substantial performance gain.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] In most cases, an index is used to quickly locate the data records from which the required data is read.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] In other words, the index is only used to locate data records in the table and not to return data.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] A covering index is a special case where the index itself contains the required data fields and can answer the required data.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] To find the Name for ID 13, an index on (ID) is useful, but the record must still be read to get the Name.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] However, an index on (ID, Name) contains the required data field and eliminates the need to look up the record.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] Covering indexes are each for a specific table.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] Queries which JOIN/ access across multiple tables, may potentially consider covering indexes on more than one of these tables.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] A covering index can dramatically speed up data retrieval but may itself be large due to the additional keys, which slow down data insertion and update.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] To reduce such index size, some systems allow including non-key fields in the index.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] Non-key fields are not themselves part of the index ordering but only included at the leaf level, allowing for a covering index with less overall index size.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] This can be done in SQL with `CREATE INDEX my_index ON my_table (id) INCLUDE (name);`.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] No standard defines how to create indexes, because the ISO SQL Standard does not cover physical aspects.
[src:secondary-index/database-index] Indexes are one of the physical parts of database conception among others like storage (tablespace or filegroups).
[src:secondary-index/database-index] RDBMS vendors all give a `CREATE INDEX` syntax with some specific options that depend on their software's capabilities.
[src:secondary-index/indexes-types] PostgreSQL provides several index types: B-tree, Hash, GiST, SP-GiST, GIN, BRIN, and the extension bloom.
[src:secondary-index/indexes-types] Each index type uses a different algorithm that is best suited to different types of indexable clauses.
[src:secondary-index/indexes-types] By default, the `CREATE INDEX` command creates B-tree indexes, which fit the most common situations.
[src:secondary-index/indexes-types] The other index types are selected by writing the keyword `USING` followed by the index type name.
[src:secondary-index/indexes-types] B-trees can handle equality and range queries on data that can be sorted into some ordering.
[src:secondary-index/indexes-types] Constructs equivalent to combinations of these operators, such as `BETWEEN` and `IN`, can also be implemented with a B-tree index search.
[src:secondary-index/indexes-types] Also, an `IS NULL` or `IS NOT NULL` condition on an index column can be used with a B-tree index.
[src:secondary-index/indexes-types] The optimizer can also use a B-tree index for queries involving the pattern matching operators `LIKE` and `~` *if* the pattern is a constant and is anchored to the beginning of the string — for example, `col LIKE 'foo%'` or `col ~ '^foo'`, but not `col LIKE '%bar'`.
[src:secondary-index/indexes-types] However, if your database does not use the C locale you will need to create the index with a special operator class to support indexing of pattern-matching queries; see Section 11.10 below.
[src:secondary-index/indexes-types] It is also possible to use B-tree indexes for `ILIKE` and `~*`, but only if the pattern starts with non-alphabetic characters, i.e., characters that are not affected by upper/lower case conversion.
[src:secondary-index/indexes-types] B-tree indexes can also be used to retrieve data in sorted order.
[src:secondary-index/indexes-types] This is not always faster than a simple scan and sort, but it is often helpful.
[src:secondary-index/indexes-types] Hash indexes store a 32-bit hash code derived from the value of the indexed column.
[src:secondary-index/indexes-types] Hence, such indexes can only handle simple equality comparisons.
[src:secondary-index/indexes-types] GiST indexes are not a single kind of index, but rather an infrastructure within which many different indexing strategies can be implemented.
[src:secondary-index/indexes-types] Accordingly, the particular operators with which a GiST index can be used vary depending on the indexing strategy (the *operator class*).
[src:secondary-index/indexes-types] (See Section 9.11 for the meaning of these operators.) The GiST operator classes included in the standard distribution are documented in Table 65.1.
[src:secondary-index/indexes-types] Many other GiST operator classes are available in the `contrib` collection or as separate projects.
[src:secondary-index/indexes-types] which finds the ten places closest to a given target point.
[src:secondary-index/indexes-types] The ability to do this is again dependent on the particular operator class being used.
[src:secondary-index/indexes-types] In Table 65.1, operators that can be used in this way are listed in the column “Ordering Operators”.
[src:secondary-index/indexes-types] SP-GiST indexes, like GiST indexes, offer an infrastructure that supports various kinds of searches.
[src:secondary-index/indexes-types] SP-GiST permits implementation of a wide range of different non-balanced disk-based data structures, such as quadtrees, k-d trees, and radix trees (tries).
[src:secondary-index/indexes-types] (See Section 9.11 for the meaning of these operators.) The SP-GiST operator classes included in the standard distribution are documented in Table 65.2.
[src:secondary-index/indexes-types] Like GiST, SP-GiST supports “nearest-neighbor” searches.
[src:secondary-index/indexes-types] For SP-GiST operator classes that support distance ordering, the corresponding operator is listed in the “Ordering Operators” column in Table 65.2.
[src:secondary-index/indexes-types] GIN indexes are “inverted indexes” which are appropriate for data values that contain multiple component values, such as arrays.
[src:secondary-index/indexes-types] An inverted index contains a separate entry for each component value, and can efficiently handle queries that test for the presence of specific component values.
[src:secondary-index/indexes-types] Like GiST and SP-GiST, GIN can support many different user-defined indexing strategies, and the particular operators with which a GIN index can be used vary depending on the indexing strategy.
[src:secondary-index/indexes-types] (See Section 9.19 for the meaning of these operators.) The GIN operator classes included in the standard distribution are documented in Table 65.3.
[src:secondary-index/indexes-types] Many other GIN operator classes are available in the `contrib` collection or as separate projects.
[src:secondary-index/indexes-types] BRIN indexes (a shorthand for Block Range INdexes) store summaries about the values stored in consecutive physical block ranges of a table.
[src:secondary-index/indexes-types] Thus, they are most effective for columns whose values are well-correlated with the physical order of the table rows.
[src:secondary-index/indexes-types] Like GiST, SP-GiST and GIN, BRIN can support many different indexing strategies, and the particular operators with which a BRIN index can be used vary depending on the indexing strategy.
[src:secondary-index/indexes-types] For data types that have a linear sort order, the indexed data corresponds to the minimum and maximum values of the values in the column for each block range.
[src:secondary-index/indexes-types] The BRIN operator classes included in the standard distribution are documented in Table 65.4.
[src:secondary-index/indexes-types] If you see anything in the documentation that is not correct, does not match your experience with the particular feature or requires further clarification, please use this form to report a documentation issue.
[src:secondary-index/inverted-index] The purpose of an inverted index is to allow fast full-text searches, at a cost of increased processing when a document is added to the database.
[src:secondary-index/inverted-index] The inverted file may be the database file itself, rather than its index.
[src:secondary-index/inverted-index] It is the most popular data structure used in document retrieval systems, used on a large scale for example in search engines.
[src:secondary-index/inverted-index] Additionally, several significant general-purpose mainframe-based database management systems have used inverted list architectures, including ADABAS, DATACOM/DB, and Model 204.
[src:secondary-index/inverted-index] There are two main variants of inverted indexes: A **record-level inverted index** (or **inverted file index** or just **inverted file**) contains a list of references to documents for each word.
[src:secondary-index/inverted-index] A **word-level inverted index** (or **full inverted index** or **inverted list**) additionally contains the positions of each word within a document.
[src:secondary-index/inverted-index] The latter form offers more functionality (like phrase searches), but needs more processing power and space to be created.
[src:secondary-index/inverted-index] The inverted index data structure is a central component of a typical search engine indexing algorithm.
[src:secondary-index/inverted-index] A goal of a search engine implementation is to optimize the speed of the query: find the documents where word X occurs.
[src:secondary-index/inverted-index] Once a forward index is developed, which stores lists of words per document, it is next inverted to develop an inverted index.
[src:secondary-index/inverted-index] Querying the forward index would require sequential iteration through each document and to each word to verify a matching document.
[src:secondary-index/inverted-index] The time, memory, and processing resources to perform such a query are not always technically realistic.
[src:secondary-index/inverted-index] Instead of listing the words per document in the forward index, the inverted index data structure is developed which lists the documents per word.
[src:secondary-index/inverted-index] With the inverted index created, the query can be resolved by jumping to the word ID (via random access) in the inverted index.
[src:secondary-index/inverted-index] In pre-computer times, concordances to important books were manually assembled.
[src:secondary-index/inverted-index] These were effectively inverted indexes with a small amount of accompanying commentary that required a tremendous amount of effort to produce.
[src:secondary-index/inverted-index] In bioinformatics, inverted indexes are very important in the sequence assembly of short fragments of sequenced DNA.
[src:secondary-index/inverted-index] One way to find the source of a fragment is to search for it against a reference DNA sequence.
[src:secondary-index/inverted-index] A small number of mismatches (due to differences between the sequenced DNA and reference DNA, or errors) can be accounted for by dividing the fragment into smaller fragments—at least one subfragment is likely to match the reference DNA sequence.
[src:secondary-index/inverted-index] The matching requires constructing an inverted index of all substrings of a certain length from the reference DNA sequence.
[src:secondary-index/inverted-index] Since the human DNA contains more than 3 billion base pairs, and we need to store a DNA substring for every index and a 32-bit integer for index itself, the storage requirement for such an inverted index would probably be in the tens of gigabytes.
[src:secondary-index/inverted-index] For historical reasons, inverted list compression and bitmap compression were developed as separate lines of research, and only later were recognized as solving essentially the same problem.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Popular search engines focus on the full-text indexing of online, natural language documents.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Media types such as pictures, video, audio, and graphics are also searchable.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Meta search engines reuse the indices of other services and do not store a local index whereas cache-based search engines permanently store the index along with the corpus.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Unlike full-text indices, partial-text services restrict the depth indexed to reduce index size.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Larger services typically perform indexing at a predetermined time interval due to the required time and processing costs, while agent-based search engines index in real time.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] The purpose of storing an index is to optimize speed and performance in finding relevant documents for a search query.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Without an index, the search engine would scan every document in the corpus, which would require considerable time and computing power.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] For example, while an index of 10,000 documents can be queried within milliseconds, a sequential scan of every word in 10,000 large documents could take hours.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] The additional computer storage required to store the index, as well as the considerable increase in the time required for an update to take place, are traded off for the time saved during information retrieval.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] How data enters the index, or how words or subject features are added to the index during text corpus traversal, and whether multiple indexers can work asynchronously.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] The indexer must first check whether it is updating old content or adding new content.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] , that is, whether information should be data compressed or filtered.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] The speed of finding an entry in a data structure, compared with how quickly it can be updated or removed, is a central focus of computer science.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] How important it is for the service to be reliable.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Search engine architectures vary in the way indexing is performed and in methods of index storage to meet the various design factors.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Figuratively structured like a tree, supports linear time lookup.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] , which is important for search engine indexing.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] A major drawback is that storing a word in the tree may require space beyond that required to store the word itself.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] A major challenge in the design of search engines is the management of serial computing processes.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] There are many opportunities for race conditions and coherent faults.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] For example, a new document is added to the corpus and the index must be updated, but the index simultaneously needs to continue responding to search queries.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] This is a collision between two competing tasks.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Consider that authors are producers of information, and a web crawler is the consumer of this information, grabbing the text and storing it in a cache (or corpus).
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] The forward index is the consumer of the information produced by the corpus, and the inverted index is the consumer of information produced by the forward index.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] This is commonly referred to as a **producer-consumer model**.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] The indexer is the producer of searchable information and users are the consumers that need to search.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] The challenge is magnified when working with distributed storage and distributed processing.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] In an effort to scale with larger amounts of indexed information, the search engine's architecture may involve distributed computing, where the search engine consists of several machines operating in unison.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] This increases the possibilities for incoherency and makes it more difficult to maintain a fully synchronized, distributed, parallel architecture.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Many search engines incorporate an inverted index when evaluating a search query to quickly locate documents containing the words in a query and then rank these documents by relevance.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Because the inverted index stores a list of the documents containing each word, the search engine can use direct access to find the documents associated with each word in the query in order to retrieve the matching documents quickly.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] This index can only determine whether a word exists within a particular document, since it stores no information regarding the frequency and position of the word; it is therefore considered to be a Boolean index.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Such an index determines which documents match a query but does not rank matched documents.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] In some designs the index includes additional information such as the frequency of each word in each document or the positions of a word in each document.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Position information enables the search algorithm to identify word proximity to support searching for phrases; frequency can be used to help in ranking the relevance of documents to the query.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Such topics are the central research focus of information retrieval.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] The inverted index is a sparse matrix, since not all words are present in each document.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] To reduce computer storage memory requirements, it is stored differently from a two dimensional array.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] The index is similar to the term document matrices employed by latent semantic analysis.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] The inverted index can be considered a form of a hash table.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] In some cases the index is a form of a binary tree, which requires additional storage but may reduce the lookup time.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] In larger indices the architecture is typically a distributed hash table.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] For phrase searching, a specialized form of an inverted index called a positional index is used.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] A positional index not only stores the ID of the document containing the token but also the exact position(s) of the token within the document in the postings list.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] The occurrences of the phrase specified in the query are retrieved by navigating these postings list and identifying the indexes at which the desired terms occur in the expected order (the same as the order in the phrase).
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Check that this occurrence is immediately after the occurrence of "first".
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] If not, continue to the next occurrence of "first".
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] The postings lists can be navigated using a binary search in order to minimize the time complexity of this procedure.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] The inverted index is filled via a merge or rebuild.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] A rebuild is similar to a merge but first deletes the contents of the inverted index.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] The architecture may be designed to support incremental indexing, where a merge identifies the document or documents to be added or updated and then parses each document into words.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] For technical accuracy, a merge conflates newly indexed documents, typically residing in virtual memory, with the index cache residing on one or more computer hard drives.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] After parsing, the indexer adds the referenced document to the document list for the appropriate words.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] The inverted index is so named because it is an inversion of the forward index.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] The forward index stores a list of words for each document.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] The rationale behind developing a forward index is that as documents are parsed, it is better to intermediately store the words per document.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] The delineation enables asynchronous system processing, which partially circumvents the inverted index update bottleneck.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] The forward index is sorted to transform it to an inverted index.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] The forward index is essentially a list of pairs consisting of a document and a word, collated by the document.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Converting the forward index to an inverted index is only a matter of sorting the pairs by the words.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] In this regard, the inverted index is a word-sorted forward index.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Generating or maintaining a large-scale search engine index represents a significant storage and processing challenge.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Many search engines utilize a form of compression to reduce the size of the indices on disk.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Consider the following scenario for a full text, Internet search engine.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Given this scenario, an uncompressed index (assuming a non-conflated, simple, index) for 2 billion web pages would need to store 500 billion word entries.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] At 1 byte per character, or 5 bytes per word, this would require 2500 gigabytes of storage space alone.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] This space requirement may be even larger for a fault-tolerant distributed storage architecture.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Depending on the compression technique chosen, the index can be reduced to a fraction of this size.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] The tradeoff is the time and processing power required to perform compression and decompression.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Notably, large scale search engine designs incorporate the cost of storage as well as the costs of electricity to power the storage.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Document parsing breaks apart the components (words) of a document or other form of media for insertion into the forward and inverted indices.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] The words found are called *tokens*, and so, in the context of search engine indexing and natural language processing, parsing is more commonly referred to as tokenization.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] It is also sometimes called word boundary disambiguation, tagging, text segmentation, content analysis, text analysis, text mining, concordance generation, speech segmentation, lexing, or lexical analysis.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] The terms 'indexing', 'parsing', and 'tokenization' are used interchangeably in corporate slang.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Natural language processing is the subject of continuous research and technological improvement.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Tokenization presents many challenges in extracting the necessary information from documents for indexing to support quality searching.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Tokenization for indexing involves multiple technologies, the implementation of which are commonly kept as corporate secrets.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] The goal during tokenization is to identify words for which users will search.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Language-specific logic is employed to properly identify the boundaries of words, which is often the rationale for designing a parser for each language supported (or for groups of languages with similar boundary markers and syntax).
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] These techniques are language-dependent, as the syntax varies among languages.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Documents do not always clearly identify the language of the document or represent it accurately.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] In tokenizing the document, some search engines attempt to automatically identify the language of the document.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] In order to correctly identify which bytes of a document represent characters, the file format must be correctly handled.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Search engines that support multiple file formats must be able to correctly open and access the document and be able to tokenize the characters of the document.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] The quality of the natural language data may not always be perfect.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] An unspecified number of documents, particularly on the Internet, do not closely obey proper file protocol.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] characters may be mistakenly encoded into various parts of a document.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Without recognition of these characters and appropriate handling, the index quality or indexer performance could degrade.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Unlike literate humans, computers do not understand the structure of a natural language document and cannot automatically recognize words and sentences.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] To a computer, a document is only a sequence of bytes.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Computers do not 'know' that a space character separates words in a document.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Instead, humans must program the computer to identify what constitutes an individual or distinct word referred to as a token.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Such a program is commonly called a tokenizer or parser or lexer.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Many search engines, as well as other natural language processing software, incorporate specialized programs for parsing, such as YACC or Lex.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] During tokenization, the parser identifies sequences of characters that represent words and other elements, such as punctuation, which are represented by numeric codes, some of which are non-printing control characters.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] The parser can also identify entities such as email addresses, phone numbers, and URLs.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] When identifying each token, several characteristics may be stored, such as the token's case (upper, lower, mixed, proper), language or encoding, lexical category (part of speech, like 'noun' or 'verb'), position, sentence number, sentence position, length, and line number.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] If the search engine supports multiple languages, a common initial step during tokenization is to identify each document's language; many of the subsequent steps are language dependent (such as stemming and part of speech tagging).
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Language recognition is the process by which a computer program attempts to automatically identify, or categorize, the language of a document.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Other names for language recognition include language classification, language analysis, language identification, and language tagging.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Automated language recognition is the subject of ongoing research in natural language processing.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Finding which language the words belongs to may involve the use of a language recognition chart.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] If the search engine supports multiple document formats, documents must be prepared for tokenization.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] The challenge is that many document formats contain formatting information in addition to textual content.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] For example, HTML documents contain HTML tags, which specify formatting information such as new line starts, bold emphasis, and font size or style.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] If the search engine were to ignore the difference between content and 'markup', extraneous information would be included in the index, leading to poor search results.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Format analysis is the identification and handling of the formatting content embedded within documents which controls the way the document is rendered on a computer screen or interpreted by a software program.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Format analysis is also referred to as structure analysis, format parsing, tag stripping, format stripping, text normalization, text cleaning and text preparation.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] The challenge of format analysis is further complicated by the intricacies of various file formats.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Certain file formats are proprietary with very little information disclosed, while others are well documented.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Options for dealing with various formats include using a publicly available commercial parsing tool that is offered by the organization which developed, maintains, or owns the format, and writing a custom parser.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Some search engines support inspection of files that are stored in a compressed or encrypted file format.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] When working with a compressed format, the indexer first decompresses the document; this step may result in one or more files, each of which must be indexed separately.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Format analysis can involve quality improvement methods to avoid including 'bad information' in the index.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Content can manipulate the formatting information to include additional content.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Some search engines incorporate section recognition, the identification of major parts of a document, prior to tokenization.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Not all the documents in a corpus read like a well-written book, divided into organized chapters and pages.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Many documents on the web, such as newsletters and corporate reports, contain erroneous content and side-sections that do not contain primary material (that which the document is about).
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] For example, articles on the Wikipedia website display a side menu with links to other web pages.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Some file formats, like HTML or PDF, allow for content to be displayed in columns.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Even though the content is displayed, or rendered, in different areas of the view, the raw markup content may store this information sequentially.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Words that appear sequentially in the raw source content are indexed sequentially, even though these sentences and paragraphs are rendered in different parts of the computer screen.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] If search engines index this content as if it were normal content, the quality of the index and search quality may be degraded due to the mixed content and improper word proximity.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Section analysis may require the search engine to implement the rendering logic of each document, essentially an abstract representation of the actual document, and then index the representation instead.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] For example, some content on the Internet is rendered via JavaScript.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] If the search engine does not render the page and evaluate the JavaScript within the page, it would not 'see' this content in the same way and would index the document incorrectly.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Given that some search engines do not bother with rendering issues, many web page designers avoid displaying content via JavaScript or use the Noscript Archived 2020-07-07 at the Wayback Machine tag to ensure that the web page is indexed properly.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] At the same time, this fact can also be exploited to cause the search engine indexer to 'see' different content than the viewer.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Indexing often has to recognize the HTML tags to organize priority.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Indexing low priority to high margin to labels like *strong* and *link* to optimize the order of priority if those labels are at the beginning of the text could not prove to be relevant.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Some indexers like Google and Bing ensure that the search engine does not take the large texts as relevant source due to strong type system compatibility.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Meta tag indexing plays an important role in organizing and categorizing web content.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Specific documents often contain embedded meta information such as author, keywords, description, and language.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] For HTML pages, the meta tag contains keywords which are also included in the index.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Earlier Internet search engine technology would only index the keywords in the meta tags for the forward index; the full document would not be parsed.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] At that time full-text indexing was not as well established, nor was computer hardware able to support such technology.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] The design of the HTML markup language initially included support for meta tags for the very purpose of being properly and easily indexed, without requiring tokenization.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] As the Internet grew through the 1990s, many brick-and-mortar corporations went 'online' and established corporate websites.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] The keywords used to describe webpages (many of which were corporate-oriented webpages similar to product brochures) changed from descriptive to marketing-oriented keywords designed to drive sales by placing the webpage high in the search results for specific search queries.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] The fact that these keywords were subjectively specified was leading to spamdexing, which drove many search engines to adopt full-text indexing technologies in the 1990s.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Search engine designers and companies could only place so many 'marketing keywords' into the content of a webpage before draining it of all interesting and useful information.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Given that conflict of interest with the business goal of designing user-oriented websites which were 'sticky', the customer lifetime value equation was changed to incorporate more useful content into the website in hopes of retaining the visitor.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] In this sense, full-text indexing was more objective and increased the quality of search engine results, as it was one more step away from subjective control of search engine result placement, which in turn furthered research of full-text indexing technologies.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] In desktop search, many solutions incorporate meta tags to provide a way for authors to further customize how the search engine will index content from various files that is not evident from the file content.
[src:secondary-index/search-engine-indexing] Desktop search is more under the control of the user, while Internet search engines must focus more on the full text index.
